			<part part_index="3" name="GravityLight" page="0" source="2">
      	<article allWordsNum="197">
            	<![CDATA[
Do you want a lamp for $5 that does not require any electrical power source?
It may sound like an impossible dream, but two designers in London have come up with a new light powered by gravity (重力).
It's easy to take our electric lights for granted. Many people in developing counties don't have the luxury of electric lights and have to use kerosene lamps (煤油灯) to brighten the night. Kerosene costs money and breathing the smoke is dangerous to our health. A new light powered by gravity could be a better solution to lighting needs.
The GravityLight doesn't need to be recharged through solar cells (太阳能蓄电池). It doesn't use batteries at all. It's powered by the same force that keeps our feet on the ground. A weight attached to the light takes three seconds to lift up, but lasts 30 minutes of light.
The GravityLight may be used as an emergency light or camping light in the developed world, but its impact on the lives of people in developing countries could be great. It's healthier and cheaper than kerosene, and less expensive than solar. What's more, the GravityLight requires only a bag of rocks or sand to provide weight!
   	]]>
            </article>
